@node "gr2" "AmiTamgotchi V0.5"

@{fg shine} Amitamagotchi V0.5@{fg text}

 No doubt you'll have heard these things bleeping away everywhere
you go and every child you see seems to be holding one of these
these days. Yes, i'm talking about those Tamagotchi's from Bandi,
a big craze has swept the world and the only place you (were) safe
from them was your Amiga but that has now all changed.

 Amitamagotchi is the third one of the Amiga Tamagotchi's i've
downloaded but the other two weren't that good to be honest so
this is the one i've decided to review. As you all probably know
what Tamgotchi is and what one ruffly looks like I won't go into
to much detail over the cosmetics of it, but just to give you an
idea heres a little run down.

 Upon loading Amitamagotchi you are presented with a good looking
GUI, the options enclued Start, Load, Save, Prefs and Quit. Once
clicking on Start a window will open which is quite big and doesn't
really fit into the corner of your screen as it's a bit to big. You
will then see the egg in the middle, options around the outside of
the egg and three buttons at the bottom of the window.

 You will have to wait around 5 minutes for the egg to hatch but you
can go off and write a letter or play a WB game as it will beep as
soon as it hatches. Most of the options work but as this is only
a beta version some don't. You can feed, play, clean and discipline
at the moment with the rest of the functions implented later. The
save and load option works alright but you have to run the program
and then load otherwise the screen will mess up if you load from the
start menu, the Author doesn't recommend you use the Load and Save
option as he hasn't sorted them out totally yet, but they worked
fine for me.

 Overall this is a good Amiga Tamagotchi if you like these things,
although not as good as the real thing, as it only comes to life
when you run it. My main concern with AmiTamagotchi is that it
eats CPU like anything, I tried running dopus while the little
blighter was running and it took quite a while but overall a nice
program to keep you happy.

