@node "gr3" "TFX"

@{fg shine} TFX@{fg text}

 As you might know TFX was given away on the October issue
of CUAmiga so we prase them for bringing us this execllent
game. They gave it away on the cover CD but if your like
me and don't have access to a CD-Rom you can send away
for the 11 disks for a bargin price of £4.50 including
P&P. Anyway on with the game.

 As soon as you load up the game you know your in for a
real treat, the music is very atmosferic and even the
credits are presented well. You come to the main menu
which funily enough still has the compiled date and
beta version number what Ocean put on the game themselves
so something tells me this is not the FULL, FULL version
but it is 99% complete and is not just going to do nothing
once you get so far through so don't worry ;).

 You get options to either train, simulator, check stats
and things like that and start game. Training if you didn't
know is getting you used to the controls which is advisable
if you havn't played it before just to get you into the
swing of things. The simulator is another type of training
mode but your not actually flying, your in some kind of
simulator put in a position that you might be when your in
head-to-head battle with someone. There are various stats
options to check like who is top pilot but thats to boring to
go into here and is not worth mentioning.

 If your like me you'll probably want to jump in straight
away so you'll jump at the chance on starting a new game. Once
you've entered you forename, surname and nickname/handle
your thrown in at the deep end and get a lecture off some
top important bloke, oh yes! Then you proceed to the game.

 In game you don't have to take off which is good and saves
time, there are different levels of detail you can choose
from, from high detail and textures to low detail and textures
turned off. I have looked at high detail and everything that
makes the game look better and I wish I had a good enough
machine to get it running at that speed because the view is
incredible. As usual though i'm stuck with low detail and
nearly every fancy gadjet Off :( Don't worry though if your
just a basic 020 owner at least you get to play the game
at a good speed even if the view isn't so hot.

 After you've increased the speed a little and get the hang
of the controls you can probably go into timewarp which
sends the game a bit quicker, once your near enemy planes
switch off timewarp and get ready for a dogfight, the
best tactic is to lock on and fire before one of the planes
reaches you, as effect you get a litte voice saying locked on
and someone from another friendly aircraft saying "good shot"
and "looks like a lizard" just to add excitment to the game.

 There is so much in TFX that could be explained but it would
probably make AIO 1000 pages bigger and would unfortuanally
take up to much time to write. I hope that i've give you an
idea of how good it is because this game is great. Make sure
you buy the CUAmiga to take up the offer. This IS probably
the BEST flight sim on the Amiga ever!

