@node "ur3" "OPTYCDPlayer"

@{fg shine} OPTYCDPlayer 2.0@{fg text}

 Looking around the Aminet the other day, I decided to investigate the
new batch of audio cd players available. I personally still use
MCDPlayer, which is included in the AmiCDFS archive, and find it a
small, friendly player, which fits my needs perfectly. Optycdplayer,
is an MUI application, which brings with it all the pros and cons of
this piece of software. Many Amiga applications now use MUI, and I
assume that most of you will know about these pros and cons, so I
won't go into them again! At first glance, Optycdplayer's screen seemed
very "busy", almost cluttered, and whilst moving from screen to screen
was quite fast, I felt that the GUI was still overly complicated. Maybe
this was due to the wealth of features which are available, but
sometimes small and beautiful wins! If you need to sample directly from
CD however, Optycdplayer comes into its own, able to convert samples
into many formats using AHI, and so, copyright restrictions apart, you
can then use these samples elsewhere. Programming the CD title and
track titles is also fairly swift, and these can be organised into a
database, of which 4000+ are included for you lazy people. After an
hours or so of playing, I felt more at ease with the GUI, and maybe
could get used to it, but I still felt that I would go back to my old
favourite MCDPlayer. If I was in need of ripping a sample direct from
CD however, then Optycdplayer would be my first choice, however dodgy
the legal implications are!

Overall then, a nice audio Cd player - perhaps a little overcomplicated
and a messy GUI!

