@{fg shine} It's down to us to save the Amiga@{fg text}

 I've decided to put pen to paper, or words to screen in this case and
get my views across to all you thousands of AIO readers :) For you not
interested in this subject i'll let you into what it's about. This
text is about us saving the AMiGA and how it is down to us so if you
don't want to listen go somewhere else, i'm not forcing you to read
this!

 The AMiGA, the best computer to millions all over the world had survived
for over 10 years but it has not survived this long by BIG companys 
producing thing for the Amiga and supporting it, it is down to us the 
users of the AMiGA that have saved it upto now and can continue to keep 
it alive as long as we support it. For about 3 or 4 years now no big
company has _really_ owned the Amiga or done anything to keep it going,
if us the user was not so supportive of the Amiga it would have died
years ago. So for that I thank all Amiga users for staying with the
Amiga, but we need to keep this support going, we need to register
shareware programs that we use regularly, we need to boast the powers
of the Amiga to the rest of the world and most of all we need to support
Amiga, Inc and any developers in the Amiga world that have the power
to change or keep things going. 

 Programmers mostly program for the fun of it and they program something
that is of use to them, but noone likes to upload a file and freely 
distribute their hard work and get no response or funds back from it. 
People moan on about registrations being to high, but think of all the
hard work and effort that the developer has put in, think of his
electricity bill and think of all the time he has spent producing that
product so you can use, when to be honest he could of said, "i'd
rather go out with my mates down the pub" or do something more 
interesting than sit in front of his computer for hours, days, months
and even years on end. Even if you can't afford registration or even
if the author doesn't ask for any payment, an email of gratitude or
letting the author know what you liked or disliked about the program
makes his or her job so much more fun to do.

 The day users stop supporting the Amiga and think that we can leave 
it up to companys is the day that the Amiga DIES. It would be a great
shame to waste what we have just because other mindless computer
users disagree with are computer. Stick with me and make the Amiga
live on. In 1 year Gateway 2000 say that new Amigas will be out so
think that if we can just hold on that long we will have a new
machine which will be 10 times more powerful and attract all those
other computer users back to the glory days of the Amiga, the main
home and even work computer.

