@node "fe5" "Upgrade Kickstart chips"

@{fg shine} Upgrade Kickstart chips from 3.0 to 3.1@{fg text}

@{b}The Product@{ub}

Kickstart 3.1 ROMs for Amiga 1200.
Price £29.95 plus £2.50 delivery charge.

@{b}NB:@{ub} There are different versions for older Amigas.

Workbench 3.1 was copied from CU Amiga CD No.15.

@{b}Supplier@{ub}

Power Computing
Unit 82a
Singer Way
Kempston
MK42 7PU
Tel 01234 851500
Fax 01234 855400

@{b}Installation
------------@{ub}

@{b}1. Installing the chips.@{ub}


  I received two ROMs provided in a small black box delivered in a
well packed box with two sheets of instructions.

  First I made a backup of my Workbench partition using Quarterback onto
a ZIP disk. I also took the opportunity to backup the ROM itself using
the GrabKick utility to a file. It may be come in handy for softkicking
for certain situations.

  After reading the instructions provided by Power Computing, I switched
off my Amiga and removed all the peripherals and cable from the back the
A1200.

  Now since most IC (or chips) can be damaged by static, I earthed myself
on the nearest radiator. I then turned the computer upside down and
removed the screws which held the top half of the computer. I turned the
computer the right way up and lifted off the cover.

  Underneath the keyboard, in the middle of the shielding are two well
exposed chips. These are the kickstart v39 ROM chips. I wrote down the
position and orientation of the chips and which chip was located in which
socket (two different numbers were on each chip. The one above was
numbered 1044 and the one below was 1043). The orientation is determined
by a little notch on the left edge of each chip. This notch was located on
the left side of the chip (NB: do not go by the writing on the chip).

  To give me more room I removed the keyboard and carefully disconnected
the keyboard ribbon near the back of the Amiga.

  I used a small flat bed screwdriver to slowly lift the old ROM chips
out. The best way to do this is to lever alternately from each side. Once
these chips were removed I placed them in a handy black IC bag for safe
keeping.

  The new ROM chips have to placed in a certain way on the motherboard.
They are labeled as U6B and U6A. The U6B goes into the top socket and the
U6A in the bottom socket. Also, there are more holes on the ROM sockets
than there are legs on the ROM chips. The ROMs must go into the right
most sockets leaving 2 holes on the left hand side. The notch must also
match the orientation of the old sockets. In my case the notches should
appear on the left side.

 I discovered that the legs of the ROM chips were too far apart for them
to fit properly in the sockets. I carefully, pressed each side of the ROM
legs on the metal shielding so eventually they are just narrowed enough
for them to fit into the sockets. I repeated this for the second ROM. I
them carefully pressed them into the sockets so that they clicked into
place. I then reconnected the keyboard and replaced the top cover but did
not screw it into place. I reconnected the mouse and monitor and the
power and switched on. It booted first time! Running the VERSION command
gave me a V40.68 kick start ROM!

  The Amiga was screwed back together and all the peripherals were
reattached for the next part of the installation - Workbench 3.1.

@{b}2. Installing the software@{ub}

  Although I opted to get the ROM chip only, some people may have got the
full Kickstart/Workbench package. This may be better for some people as
it has the full software collection.

  I had earlier made myself a Workbench 3.1 disk set using the software
available from the CUCDs. The majority of the Workbench libraries, devices
and utilities are available here (see Libs, S, L, Devs, Classes, Tools,
System and Utilities). Since WB3.1 is not much different from 3.0 I knew
what I was looking for. The most important files are the v40 libraries.
Not all the libraries are updated but the main ones to look for are:

 amigaguide, asl, commodities, datatypes, iffparse, locale, lowlevel,
 nonvolatile, realtime, version and workbench.


Most sure you backup important files such as the startup-sequence and
any DOSDrivers (esp. CD0) incase they get overwritten by WB3.1's versions.
I copied the Workbench, Extras disks only as they had the most changes,
to my system disk.

I rebooted my Amiga and discovered a couple of problems:

1. I had my startup-sequence overwritten (I was using my CD boot script
before). I recovered this from a backup copy off my Zappo disks.

2. There was a problem loading my Workbench background pattern as it
did not recognise the datatypes library. Replacing the library with a v39
temporarily solved the problem.

   I asked someone via the Pure-Amiga mailing list and discovered that my
startup-sequence requires an extra line to recognise the new v40 datatype
s:

C:ADDDATATYPES REFRESH

once this was added and the v40 datatypes library reinstalled I got it
working again. Finally, one more thing. Workbench 3.1 CLI programs do
have their pure bits set, so you should download Fix_WB1.3.lha from
Aminet to fix the missing bits for various programs.

I now have a fully functional WB 3.1 Amiga.


@{b}Conclusion@{ub}

  This is the only OS upgrade I have performed on my machine besides
adding third party software to make it more up to date. I found it very
easy to follow and as long as you double-check your work before switching
on it should be trouble free.
  I do recommend you to upgrade to WB 3.1 for several reasons. First you
will now get a more stable and faster Amiga as WB 3.1 has loads of bug
fixes and speed ups since 3.0. KS 3.1 has a feature to allow some hard
disks to spin up before booting. Also, you can now use some of the more
recent hardware drivers such as the v43/44 FFS and Picasso software
drivers.
  Upgrading to 3.1 will also prepare you for the next round of OS upgrades
which will be software onlu ie WB 3.5 which Amiga Intl will be releasing
within the next six months. Of course you could get the ROMs and software
together when it released and may save some money.


