@{fg shine} Info on BBS and software@{fg text}

Bulletin Board Systems (BBS's) provide a huge amount of info
about just about everything computer related.  Okay so maybe not
as much as the world wide web, but lets face it, how many
internet providers do you know that don't charge a subscription
??
	Just about all BBS's are free of charge, apart from phone
costs of course, so if you can find a local BBS you would be
better off using it.  This month we have all the information you 
will need to set up Ncomm, a terminal emulation package to use
BBS's.
	BBS's use a system called ANSI, which are coloured IBM
characters, the style of drawing on most BBS's differ.  Most
BBS's have their own "theme", and then you get the odd few that
have the setup that comes with the bbs software.. and more often 
than not look crap :(  Most BBS's offer a variety of files
available for download (transfer to your computer), and some have 
what is called a file ratio, e.g. 5:1, which means that for every
5 files you download you have to give one.
	Some BBS's offer fidonet type mail systems on which you can
read/write messages to people all over the country, sometimes 
even to other countries depending on the size of the mail net.

	The first thing you need to obtain is a copy of a terminal 
emulation package such as Ncomm. Unfortunately it hasn't been
included with the magazine because of space limitations, your 
best bet is the aminet or a PD library.  Once you have a copy, 
and have it installed, load it up and follow the instructions
below for configuring it.

Quick Setup

Nothing under the System menu really needs to be set up, Log 
Calls logs all the calls you have made (with the telephone number
and time online).  This can be useful to keep track of your phone 
bill, a friend of mine once had to sell all his computer
equipment to pay off his phone bill, don't let this put you off
though, as long as it is kept under tabs you shouldn't end up 
with a massive phone bill.

The next two menus are the most important.

Transfer Menu:

Options - Turn on Chop files, Zmodem AutoUL, Zmodem AutoDl and 
Transfer bar.

Default directory - Select upload, then you will get a requester
in which you choose the directory you wish to send files from 
(this can however be changed at the start of the upload, it is
just the directory it will open initially).
	Then Select download and you will get another requester in 
which you should choose the directory you wish to store files you
receive in, preferably NOT a floppy disk.

Protocol - Zmodem should be selected.

Com Menu:

Baud Rate - This depends on the speed of modem you are using, 
below are what you should use for different speeds of modem:

	Modem Speed	Baud Rate

	9600	9600
	19200	19200
	14400	38400
	28800	38400
	33600	38400

Note: For the last two types of modem you may be able to use
57600, however some A1200's will not function correctly at this 
speed.

Data Length - 8 bits
Parity - None
Stop Bits - 1 bit
Duplex - Full
Handshaking - RTS/CTS (this is sometimes referred to as 7 wire 
handshaking)

Providing you are using your Amiga's built in serial port, this
is all that requires altering under this menu, however if you are
using another port, e.g. Surf Squirrel, Port Plus etc.
Select Set Device, and you will get a box to enter the device
name in (this is case sensitive).

Emulation menu:

End of line - The following should be selected
	TX EOL = CR
	RX EOL = CR

Character Set - This should be set to IBM

Screen menu:

Most of the options under this menu are purely preferential and 
will not affect the operation of Ncomm.

Phone menu:

Modem setup - To configure this you will have to refer to your
modem manual, or perhaps manufacturer.

For more in-depth information about any of these menus you should 
take a look at the instructions that come with Ncomm.

Everything should now be ready for you to use now, so save your
config (Save Config, under the System Menu), and select Phone 
book from the phone menu.  You are now in the position to add new
numbers to the phone book by pressing New.

When this is done a window containing the following text boxes 
will open:

Name	Name of the BBS System  	Backwoods BBS
Phone #	Telephone number of the system 	01463 870022
Comment	A comment (not a necessity)	Excellent


There are several others between these, but none of them should
be of any concern at the moment.

User Name	The user name you use on the system	Luigi
Password	The password you chose	AS IF :)


None of the selections below this should be altered, they are all
set from the ncomm.config.

Now select Ok, and then Save.

Now pull down the Dial menu (very end one) and select the BBS 
Name, ncomm will proceed to dial the one you choose.

Now that you have everything working and ready to call a BBS, 
here is a list of bulletin board systems you should take a look
at.


	Name	Number	Hours	Speed
	
	Backwoods BBS	01463 870022	W/E 2pm-Mid    33.6
			OTHER 9pm-Mid

	RedRum	01635 826720	24hrz   33.6
		01635 827203	24hrz   14.4

	Total Eclipse	01983 522428	24hrs  33.6

